section.section:
"Performance of duties" includes, in the case of a volunteer or career firefighter, public safety aviation employee, rescue squad member, or hazardous material response team employee:
actively participating in fighting a fire;
going to or from a fire;
performing other duties necessary to the operation or maintenance of the fire company;
actively participating in the ambulance, advanced life support, or rescue work of an advanced life support unit or a fire, ambulance, or rescue company, including going to or from an emergency or rescue;
providing emergency or rescue assistance, whether acting alone or at the direction of or with a fire, ambulance, or rescue company or advanced life support unit;
actively participating in flight operations as a crew member in a rotary or fixed wing aircraft; and
providing emergency response to a discharge of oil or a release of hazardous material or other emergency response activity.

Except as provided in subsection (j) of this section and subject to subsection (c) of this section and paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection, a death benefit of $125,000 shall be paid to the surviving spouse, child, dependent parent, or estate of each of the following individuals who is killed or dies in the performance of duties on or after January 1, 2006:
a law enforcement officer;
a correctional officer;
a volunteer or career firefighter or rescue squad member;
a sworn member of the office of State Fire Marshal;
a public safety aviation employee;
a Maryland resident who was a member of the uniform services of the United States serving in the Afghanistan or Iraq conflict; or
a hazardous material response team employee.

Except as provided in subsection (j) of this section, reasonable funeral expenses, not exceeding $10,000, shall be paid to the surviving spouse, child, parent, or estate of each of the following individuals who is killed or dies in the performance of duties:
a law enforcement officer;
a correctional officer;
a volunteer or career firefighter or rescue squad member;
a public safety aviation employee;
a sworn member of the office of State Fire Marshal; or
a hazardous material response team employee.

text.section:
If the Secretary of Public Safety and Correctional Services determines that the benefits under this section are to be paid, the benefits shall be paid:
to the decedent's surviving spouse;
if no individual is eligible under item (1) of this subsection, to each surviving child of the decedent in equal shares;
for a death benefit under subsection (b) of this section, if no individual is eligible under item (1) or (2) of this subsection, to the decedent's surviving parent, if the parent was a dependent as defined in § 152 of the Internal Revenue Code; or
for any other benefit under this section, if no individual is eligible under item (1) or (2) of this subsection, to the decedent's surviving parent; or
if no individual is eligible under item (1), (2), or (3) of this subsection, to the decedent's estate.
